{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:28:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:28:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17529"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17529"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.06,0.52,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10219"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56631"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2899"},{"type":"tags","id":"6627"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive skin tightening over her face, trunk and limbs for the past eight months. She reports difficulty opening her mouth fully and swallowing solid foods. She also describes colour changes in her fingers on exposure to cold. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked. On examination, there is diffuse skin thickening extending from her fingers to her upper arms and chest. Her face appears mask-like with reduced mouth opening. She has bibasal fine end-inspiratory crepitations on auscultation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibodies is most likely to be positive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-U1-RNP antibodies","Anti-PM-Scl antibodies","Anti-RNA polymerase III antibodies","Anti-Scl-70 antibodies","Anti-centromere antibodies"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis, characterised by widespread skin thickening extending proximal to the metacarpophalangeal joints, along with Raynaud phenomenon and early internal organ involvement (dysphagia suggesting oesophageal involvement) and likely interstitial lung disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-Scl-70 antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-topoisomerase I) are found in 30-40% of patients with diffuse systemic sclerosis and are highly specific for this condition. Their presence is associated with more severe disease and increased risk of interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-centromere antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis rather than the diffuse form. These patients usually have limited, distal skin involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-RNA polymerase III antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E can be found in diffuse systemic sclerosis but are more specifically associated with scleroderma renal crisis and increased risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-U1-RNP antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of mixed connective tissue disease rather than systemic sclerosis. They are associated with features overlapping several connective tissue diseases including systemic lupus erythematosus, polymyositis, and systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-PM-Scl antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are found in patients with polymyositis-scleroderma overlap syndrome, which typically presents with features of both myositis and limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-topoisomerase I antibodies (also known as anti-Scl-70) are typically associated with diffuse systemic sclerosis, and also a higher risk of severe interstitial lung disease."],"references":["Adigun R, Goyal A, Bansal P, Hariz A. Systemic Sclerosis (CREST syndrome). In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430875/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56631"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17529"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56631"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T15:19:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T15:22:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10219"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71160"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta